node.text:
In celebration of the beautiful history of what it is to be “Black” 

A couple of months ago I randomly met @brianrichjr and @newlegaxy_ while they performed live on Newbury St.....last night we finally partnered to live stream for a Black History Month Fundraiser

In celebration of Black History month we are donating all proceeds to two black owned non profit charitable organizations @commongroundfnd and #rainydayfund

GoFundme link is in my bio!

One day when the Glory Comes it will be ours. It’ll be ours.....Just a reminder that: Black is beautiful 

Shout out to @lexicocoa on the trombone! 🎺 and all the beautiful voices of New Legaxy Community Choir 

-Doctor Elvis

"This world is full of conflicts and full of things that cannot be reconciled. But there are moments when we can… reconcile and embrace the whole mess, and that’s what I mean by ‘Hallelujah’.

The song explains that many kinds of hallelujahs do exist, and all the perfect and broken hallelujahs have equal value. It’s a desire to affirm my faith in life....." -Leonard Cohen

So far we have lost 1.5 million lives across the world to COVID-19 related deaths. Fathers, mothers, sons and daughters...

While the holidays this year won't be the same. This year, these holidays will be our opportunity to affirm our faith in life, in love, and in each other.

I've watched nurses sacrifice themselves for their patients. Physicians with medical issues themselves, risk their own lives to take care of patients. Drivers, food industry workers, and hospital staff.... I've seen strangers go the extra mile for each other. 

Seeing the strength in our collective humanity gives us all hope...

2020 has not been perfect but it has been our cold and our broken but beautiful Hallelujah.

Happy Holidays to all of you beautiful people!

Hallelujah

The talented @williamrobinsonmd on the keys 🎹
—-
Multiple COVID screening tests and precautions were taken prior to this. Please wear your masks 😷 as we both do!
—-
#christmas
#hallelujah
@wearfigs

During my last year of Orthopedic Surgery residency I was rounding on a patient who was recovering from multiple operations for recurrent spine tumors. Her daughter asked me to sing a cover of the song 500 miles by @brennanvillines 

One year later it’s the song I opened with on @maskedsingerfox 

Here’s a toast to finding a way to make all of your dreams come true. 

Much love to all of you beautiful people,
Doctor Elvis

If you knew what I’ve had to overcome in this life...you would know that words can’t describe what it feels like to stand on that stage. Easily one of the most humbling opportunities I have ever had...

Singing those last 10 seconds and watching the Air Force Thunderbirds @afthunderbirds fly over head. Truly indescribable....

Thank you @teampenske for making this possible. 

A special thank you to the millions of healthcare workers across the country keeping America safe. 

I love all of you beautiful people,
Doctor Elvis

@williamrobinsonmd on the keys as always 

@wearfigs #nationalanthem

Last Sunday I had the honor of being part of the @iheartradio Living Room Concert which raised over $15 million dollars for Covid-19 relief! It was an honor and probably one of the most surreal moments of my life....
—-
In honor of every nurse, every physician, every custodian, every social worker, every allied healthcare worker, to all of you on the frontlines. Thank you 🙏🏽 —-
In times as dark as these....nothing shines brighter than the human spirit. So keep shining and keep climbing 🧗🏽‍♂️
—-
Also we will be releasing all of our covers on Spotify and Apple Music. All download proceeds will go towards COVId-19 relief efforts 🙏🏽
—
Love you beautiful people,
Doctor Elvis
—-
#covid #frontline #imagine

node.text:
Imagine all the people...
—-
In life, there are so many things that divide us. Religion, race, politics, social status etc and etc....But today a global pandemic brings us all together as one.
—-
Over the next few months our health care system will be tested. Millions of lives will be lost. Health care providers will be under an incredible amount of stress to save thousands of people. But when times are as dark as they are today, nothing shines brighter than the human spirit. —-
There is something beautiful about a collective struggle. And the beauty in what we are facing today is that the only way to overcome this pandemic is for us to all come together as one. —-
Nurses, doctors, students, research scientists, politicians, Uber eats drivers, cashiers, factory workers etc.....Getting through this will be hard but one thing is certain...the only way we will get through it is together, as one
—-
—
—-
“You might say that I’m a dreamer. But I’m not the only one. I hope some day that you will join us...and the world will live as one....”
—-
Thankful for my brother @w_a_robinson w_a_robinson on the piano
— 📸 @kpace1914
—-
Much love to all 7.53 billion people out there,
Doctor Elvis
—-
#covid_19 #healthcareworkers

node.text:
To the patients who will be in and out of hospital for the holidays….we wish you a Merry Christmas
—-
To the sick 5 year old who will not be at home opening presents… but instead in a hospital bed for the holidays….we wish you a Merry Christmas
---
To the healthcare providers who aren’t home with their families but instead spend Christmas day giving the gift of care and sharing the gift of life…we wish you a Merry Christmas
---
Because.….the spirit of Christmas is no better exemplified than inside the doors of a hospital….It is inside these walls that we exemplify the gift of giving. The appreciation for life. But more importantly, what it truly means to share the true spirit of Christmas…
---
Happy Holidays to all of you beautiful people out there!!
---
And as always the talented @w_a_robinson  on the keys. Camera 📸 @creative_photography_mn —-
#ohholynight #christmas #christmascarols #happyholidays

node.text:
Harvard BIDMC Spine Surgery Fellowship Complete! 

I’ve dreamed about this day for a long long time…

As a first generation Haitian kid growing up in the projects of Miami…the idea that I could one day train at world class institutions like Meharry Medical College, Mayo Clinic, and Harvard BIDMC seemed unlikely to impossible…

From getting suspended 9 times in 7th grade…..to my high school counselor telling  me I should apply to trade schools….to my college counselor telling me I likely wouldn’t get into med school if I applied…

From working at baby Gap in NYC for a year after college folding tiny human clothes. With $200 to my name trying to apply to med school ….to the long trauma call nights during residency…

The road to get here was full of effort, failure, sweat and tears. But as my grandma would say “If the mountain was smooth…you wouldn’t be able to climb it”

Go ahead and tag anyone who needs a reminder

Atlanta here we come….

@wearfigs 

With Love and Motivation,

I think you need a reminder to……Smile More. It’s free therapy. 

Nearly 150,000 people die every day across the world. So if you’re reading this that means you have LIFE…..and that’s  more than enough of a good reason to smile.

You can’t always  control what happens to you in life. But you can alway control how you respond. When life gets bad, when shit hits the fan, when things don’t go my way…..I always choose to smile. 

Life’s too short for anything else. 

Sent From Somewhere With Love ❤️ , 

Dr. Elvis 

#mensfashion #smile #smilemore #shoegame

node.text:
It’s official! I’m moving to Atlanta 🍑 to start my first practice as a Spine Surgeon at @resurgensortho One of the countries largest and most respected orthopedic surgery practices

To say this is a dream come true would be a true understatement…Ever since I was 7 I’ve wanted to be a surgeon…but the road to get here was full of “no’s”. 

From my high school counselor who told me I wouldn’t likely be able to get into a “good 4 year college” and that I should consider lowering my expectations… To my college counselor who told me I probably wouldn’t be able to get into medical school….

I’m thankful for every single hurdle and every single failure along the way….Every single one taught me how to overcome the odds we all face in life. And now here we are…

I’ve had the honor and privilege of training at some of the countries best hospitals. Harvard Beth Israel for fellowship, Mayo Clinic for residency, and Meharry Medical College for med school (the countries best HBCU in my opinion lol)…and now I’m ready to make the absolute most of it. 

I look forward to being a servant to any one who needs me. Through music and spine surgery. Excited for this next chapter with all of you! 

Also….thanking my dad who worked tirelessly as single father and Haitian immigrant sacrificing his own dreams so that I could stand here today. Much love pops

I get my peaches 🍑 out in Georgia 
ATL Shawty ✌🏾

Love you Beautiful people,
Dr. Elvis

This is what happiness in the hospital looks like 😇….when strangers come together to make music 

I met this beautifully amazing student nurse practitioner and nursing supervisor Eugene Trammell at Umass Memorial Medical Center for an anniversary celebration. This was the first time we sang together and it felt like magic 

Surgery and prescription medications only go so far in the impact we can have on our patients lives. Medicine is for the body. But music is for the soul…

As the world slowly starts to open up again. Mask restrictions are being lifted, restaurants are opening up to capacity, and we’re able to travel and see family again…

Just another reminder that music truly is medicine.

What’s your favorite throwback song that makes you happy? Comment below!

The talented Junior Boateng on the keys 🎹 

Love you beautiful people
Dr. Elvis

Today, @3M released their annual State of Science Index, and the results are incredibly encouraging: trust in science remains high, younger generations feel inspired to pursue careers in STEM, and the world is energized about protecting the planet. 

But what I find most inspiring is that 85% of Americans agree it is important to increase diversity in science. 

Diversity is a critical component in our quest to solve global challenges, including future pandemics and climate change. We need people of different colors, races, ethnicities, and backgrounds to collaborate and discover solutions to help create a better future. 

 Learn more about the state of science in 2021 at 3m.com/scienceindex (link in bio)!

Comment below: What’s your favorite science/STEM fun fact?

#3M #standwithscience #stateofscience

One year ago today.....when I sat down and sang the words “Imagine...” I had no idea the number of people it would reach but more importantly the amount of collective hope it would inspire in all of us. To say that I am humbled and honored by it all would be an understatement. Thank you to every single last one of you beautiful people...In honor of every life lost over the past year....
—-
Imagine all the people...
—-
In life, there are so many things that divide us. Religion, race, politics, social status and many more....But today a global pandemic brings us all together as one.
—-
Over the next few months our health care system will be tested. Many lives will be lost. Health care providers will be under an incredible amount of stress to save thousands of people. But when times are as dark as they are today, nothing shines brighter than the human spirit. —-
There is something beautiful about a collective struggle. And the beauty in what we are facing today is that the only way to overcome this pandemic is for us to all come together as one....
—-
Nurses, doctors, students, research scientists, politicians, Uber eats drivers, cashiers, factory workers etc.....Getting through this will be hard but one thing is certain...the only way we will get through it is together, as one
—-
“You might say that I’m a dreamer. But I’m not the only one. I hope some day that you will join us...and the world will live as one....”
—-
—-
Thankful for my brother @williamrobinsonmd on the piano
—
Much love to all 7.53 billion people out there,
Dr. Elvis

Don’t give up Son, if the mountain were smooth you would not be able to climb it...$33
—-
After I graduated from college I worked at the Gap in New York for a year while doing medical research. My goal was to save up enough money to do a post bac program in order to get into medical school.
—-
I eventually saved enough and started a post-bac program that required a 3.5 GPA for admission. At the end of the program I had a 3.4 GPA and got a “We regret to inform you....rejection letter” from every single medical school I applied to that year...
—-
“If the mountain were smooth....you would not be able to climb it”
—-
I’ve faced rejection before....but at that point all I had was $33 dollars left in my bank account. I was counting on being able to apply for early financial aid once I got into Med school as a means of getting through the summer.
—-
The next year was probably the hardest year of my life. You learn very little about yourself when all is good around you. But so much more when life forces you to understand what man you are....but more importantly forces you to decide what man you wish to become....
—-
Fast forward to now...5 months away from completing my Spine Surgery fellowship at Harvard Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center 
—-
I’ve learned the deep truth....that when life/God/the universe puts a challenge before you.....it’s only to force you to reach higher as you climb
——
Keep climbing you beautiful people. The mountain will not be smooth because if it was you would never be able to climb it.....I know from experience
——
Love, Doctor Elvis
—-
—-
📸  @justins_photography_rochester
#keepclimbing #mountains

When I was 9 years old my Haitian grandmother passed away from a sudden heart attack in her sleep…

I’ve never really known family grief until that day. You see my grandma was a beautiful strong black woman who was the definition of a true Haitian matriarch. She taught me the meaning of work but more importantly.......what defines a man is not how much he makes for himself but how much he makes for those who can not help themselves. 

It wasn’t until I became a medical student that I began to understood how devastating heart disease truly is. To this day, Heart Disease is the #1 cause of death in America and affects African Americans at a disproportionate rate. 

So when the folks at @liptonusa reached out in support of an album to raise awareness of the simple things you can do to take care of your heart health, it was a no brainer for me. We released a short EP of heart themed songs to help raise awareness and also donated $50,000 to the American Hearth Association. 

To hear the full songs: Download the link to the album in my bio!

Hopefully this is a good reminder to continue to take care of your heart health. Miss you Granma

Love you beautiful people,
Doctor Elvis
